 v0.50ŕ    Watcom and Pmode/W !                        February 25th, 1998

        !  Ok, here we go ! This is the first version of the        !
        !  C/C++ 'PMode/W and Watcom' F/X Player                    !
        !  I wrote it completle from scratch again but now almost   !
        !  nothing is written in assembler but now in C/C++ ;)      !
        !  Also, some other formats will have to wait...            !

        !  The new Credo of the F/X Player is now :                 !
        !  NO approximations, all calculations must be 100% correct !

           Changes:

           ! The sound formats and the mixer is now complete divided in two
             different programms and the play/interpretation routines of the
             sound formats are each unique and have no dependence! This will
             lead to a easy implementation of new formats and a easy
             emulation of the different soundformats or changes.

           ! CPU power is now not just taken completely but is done via
                                    MUTLITASKING
             YES, multitasking IS possible under DOS! There is now a REAL
             thread started which just gets CPU power when needed for
             refilling the soundcard buffer (FIFO) and this is NOT realized
             by polling or some stupid timer interrupt !!! EXACTLY, this
             player does not use any timer, timer IRQ or anything else
             in the system just a simple scheduler system which can only
             handle two threads, one calculation thread and one mainthread
             which is used for desktop or DOS shell ! So this player is
             perfectly made for games or demos under DOS because no timer IRQ
             is taken by the soundsystem nor it must be called several times
             in a second... no... it just stands there and makes its work!
             It seems Windows have no problems with this 'illegal' thread
             implementation via DPMI in DOS so why not use it ?

           + WAV player added (can only play at frequency of Soundcard :[ )
             I promise I will change it in the near future !
           + S3M player added (huh, was this new ?)
             99.9% accurate ST3.2 playing with REAL effect emulation not
             just what the documentation said which is only 80% right !
             There may be a 0.1% chance of things I had overseen !
             The probably BEST S3M player around !!!  ==> Try it !!!
           # a bug in my old S3M parser found which could not keep
             a effect value without an effect and if followed by a
             effect with a value of 0 it didn't use the old value

           - WideMono removed ( was only usefull on headphones :( )
           - Interpolation was removed due to new mixer

           * mixer has been now optimized to 32bit assembler and is about
             twice as fast as the last version  (thank god it's pmode :)
           ! the 16bit wide mixer is now optimized in 32bit code.
             It plays up to 32 channels with an accuracy of up to
             12 bits per sample (good with interpolation!)
           * mixer can now handle 8bit mono, 8bit stereo, 16bit mono and
             16bit stereo with signed or unsigned samples
           * the mixer has now a 256 step volume table and can do 256 steps
             left-right panning as well as (inverting-)surround
           # bug in loop mixer found and removed (thanks to RDF/Perfection)
             Was noticeable in Inside.S3M in pattern 7-8

           + three steps stability system when CPU is overloaded...
             1st step stops mixing but keeps calculating the correct
                 sample positions
             2nd step updates only the effects and patterns to keep in time
             3rd will stop all work until the CPU has some time left :P

           + command line switches and help added
           - INI file is not yet available, use command line switches instead

             YAHOO ! I am 23 years old.... but ok, this is enough ;)

---************************************************************************---

 v0.51ŕ    Interpolation                                  March 13th, 1998

           + I cut one ASM instruction in the 16bit mixer so now it needs
             only 7 instructions in mono and 8 in stereo with panning
             (counted with loop instructions). This shortcut will also be
             used in the new 32bit mixer which is in development now.

           * alpha version of the new interpolation mixer! It use a
             interpolation routine 65536 steps fine which interpolates the
             sample upward to 24bit width! A great advantage in comparison
             to the old interpolation mixer!
             But the used 16bit mixer cuts the sample down to 12bit, oops :(
             Now there is still no loop click removal yet :(

           ! I made a short S3M file which shows the problems other
             players like Cubic, DMP, MMP and so on have with some effects.
             Play it with ST3.2 or F/X and you will see how it should work ;)
             It is named FXCHECK.S3M and is 480 bytes big !

---************************************************************************---

 v0.52ŕ    loop click removal                             March 22th, 1998

           * the interpolation routine is now beta
           + first try of loop click removal for interpolation activated

---************************************************************************---

 v0.53ŕ    Soft clipping mode                             March 24th, 1998

           + SB pro now works in stereo mode

           + clipping algorithm can now be selected from hard clipping
             (the standard method) and soft clipping (logarithmic like)
             Soft clipping produces a better aliasing when clipping is
             needed but consumes also a bit more CPU power.
             Some professional amplifiers have a switch to change from
             hard to soft clipping to reduce this sort of distortion.
             Yes, we DO say 'no approximations!' but this one is an effort
             to improve quality in over-leveled Modules.

---************************************************************************---

