 v0.63ŕ    669 never dies                               October 04th, 1998

           + I added a 669 loader and player. Well, I'm not very proud on it
             and I don't want to waste more time on this. So I will not
             take any more time to test the 669 routines or make big changes.
             If there are any errors you are welcomed to share with me and
             I will, if my time allows, fix it if it's not too hard :)

           + I added keyboard handling so you can use the cursor-keys
             to move in MOD, 669, S3M or WAV forwards or backwards.
             This is a quick version like all players usually implement this
             feature but in the future this will be extended with better
             handling for 'break pattern', 'change speed' or similiar effects
             so if skipping some patterns all speed changes are also done :)

           * Uiiiii, you can start to play 16bit stereo even if you only have
             a SB 2.0 ! This of course screws up the soundcard or the DMA!
             Now it will check what is allowed with the detected soundcard
             and overwrite wrong <MAD?> switches or default values!
             I hope Beo is now happy with this solution ;-)

           * Hm, it seems that Windows 95 does not like my DOS multitasking
             extension anymore. This happens due of my keyboard handling
             routines so the F/X player did not work under Win95 anymore :(
             So the Windows 95 port is now really needed :)

---************************************************************************---

 v0.64ŕ    Windows is back !                            October 15th, 1998

          * HA! I really did not believe that Win95 sucks so much and did not
            accept my play-routines anymore! But after I had my first look
            to the fresh OpenCP sources I got an idea! Yeah, it was a bug in
            my IRQ routines of the soundcard! I really should remember that
            the stack (which I set up on my own) is done from top to bottom
            not vice-versa! :-D
            So no wonder it wrote somewhere into memory and Windows screw up!
            So since the last IRQ changes in v0.60 this was quite buggy!

          # Made a few little bugfixes, some here, some there, nothing special.

            Big thanks to Pascal and of course KB who made a cool piece of
            software and give the source to the public :)

---************************************************************************---

 v0.65ŕ                                                 October 25th, 1998

          # bug in MOD sample interpreter
            If you have a MOD with loop bigger than sample itself causes
            crackles and clicks. The same if the loop starts behind sampleend.

